      "writtenOn": "2026-04-21T16:45:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t see `openbmc/openbmc` listed here and there is a huge gap in your design: how do you specify which drives are managed by this proposal.\n\nphosphor-state-manager was written before entity-manager so it isn\u0027t unexpected that the integration between the two is very weak; effectively non-existent for \"how many chassis and hosts\" do we have.  PSM hard-coded this into openbmc recipe files per-platform.\n\nWhen we start to move into sub-devices, I think integration with EM becomes far more important:\n- How do you express the relationship between a host and a sub-device?\n- How do you express the relationship between a sub-device inventory (FRU) and state management?\n- How do you handle dynamic detection of devices and/or configurations where some devices are not present?  Drives, for example, can have N NVMe slots with only M of them populated.  We shouldn\u0027t show Redfish content for power control of empty slots.",
      "revId": "4ff327287324289852a2ad878af9b0c353facc09",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f3e72aec_366f9722",
        "filename": "designs/drive-state-manager.md",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 176,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002134
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-22T15:36:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thank you for the detailed questions. All addressed in the updated design under \"Entity-Manager Integration\":\n\nHost-to-device relationship: through the existing `Inventory.Decorator.ManagedHost` interface. The design\u0027s config example shows ManagedHost with HostIndex on the drive Board entity.\n\nInventory-to-state relationship: through a D-Bus association (\"inventory\", \"state\", \u003cinventory path\u003e) published by the state object. This would require a bmcweb change to follow the association endpoint instead of the current same-path lookup.\n\nDynamic detection: the daemon watches entity-manager InterfacesAdded/InterfacesRemoved. Platforms can use gpio-presence with DevicePresence Probe for SSD slots. When a device is absent, gpio-presence removes the DevicePresence interface, entity-manager tears down the Board entity, and the state daemon destroys the state object. No inventory means no Redfish resource.\n\nDetection is independent of FRU availability: drives without FRU EEPROM use GPIO presence detection, drives with FRU use FruDevice Probe, and the daemon is agnostic to the detection mechanism.",
      "parentUuid": "dc5f36db_22c950ba",
      "revId": "4ff327287324289852a2ad878af9b0c353facc09",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    }
